FBIS4-5486 "dreas070_a_94008" FBIS-EAS-94-070 Daily Report 12 Apr 1994 NORTHEAST ASIA Japan Controversy Over Successor to Hosokawa Continues Controversy Over Successor to Hosokawa Continues Watanabe on `Resolve' To Run OW1204090994 Tokyo KYODO in English 0855 GMT 12 Apr 94 OW1204090994 Tokyo KYODO English BFN [Text] Tokyo, April 12 KYODO -- Former Foreign Minister Michio Watanabe implied Tuesday [12 April] that he might leave the main opposition party, the Liberal Democratic Party (LDP), to run for a prime ministerial election in the Diet, an LDP legislator said. Watanabe, head of one of the LDP's five major factions, showed the resolve in a meeting with a group of junior LDP Diet members, called the "Liberals," which is led by Seiichi Ota. In the meeting, Ota's group urged Watanabe to run in the prime ministerial election in both houses of the Diet. Ota quoted Watanabe as saying, "(I) have an indomitable resolve." "(I) would like to form a new party to meet the request."
